  "prompt": "What are credits for in engineering?",
  "response": "In the context of engineering education, **credits** refer to the units used to measure the amount of academic work required to complete a degree program. Credits are typically assigned to courses based on factors like the number of lecture hours, lab work, and the expected amount of independent study. Here\u2019s how credits work in engineering:\n\n1. **Course Credits**:\n   - Each course is assigned a specific number of credits, usually reflecting the workload and contact hours.\n   - For example, a 3-credit course might involve 3 hours of lectures per week, while a 1-credit lab might involve 3 hours of hands-on work.\n\n2. **Degree Requirements**:\n   - Engineering degree programs require a certain number of total credits to graduate, typically ranging from **120 to 140 credits** for a bachelor\u2019s degree.\n   - These credits are distributed across **core engineering courses**, **general education requirements**, **electives**, and sometimes **capstone projects** or internships.\n\n3. **Types of Credits**:\n   - **Core Credits**: Courses specific to the engineering discipline (e.g., thermodynamics, circuit analysis).\n   - **General Education Credits**: Non-engineering courses like math, physics, humanities, or social sciences.\n   - **Elective Credits**: Courses chosen by the student based on their interests or specialization.\n\n4. **Credit Hours**:\n   - Credits are often tied to \u201ccredit hours,\u201d which represent the number of hours spent in class per week per semester.\n   - For example, a 3-credit course might meet for 3 hours per week over a 15-week semester.\n\n5. **Accumulation and Transfer**:\n   - Students accumulate credits as they complete courses.\n   - Credits can sometimes be transferred between institutions, depending on the compatibility of the courses and program requirements.\n\n6. **Importance of Credits**:\n   - Credits ensure that students meet the academic standards and workload expectations of their degree program.\n   - They also help in tracking progress toward graduation.\n\nIn summary, credits in engineering are a way to quantify and structure the academic workload required to earn an engineering degree. They ensure students gain the necessary knowledge and skills in both technical and non-technical areas.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
